 <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :rollin --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/roll.gif ALT=":rollin"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Efficient use is the nation's largest and fastest-growing energy source:<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
<br>
Yales, Your analysis re the light bulbs (Done else where) is impressive, even compelling, But for one thing! (And its still compelling despite this!)<br>
<br>
Don’t get me wrong I am all for improving the efficiency of our day-to-day technology (with certain reservations which I’d gladly tell you about <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ) but it is a mistake to look at any of these things in isolation.<br>
<br>
The point I am making is that improvements in efficiency do NOT generally result in reduced consumption. I know this seems counter-intuitive but in practice what tends to happen is that improved efficiency tends to be translated into improved standards of living rather than reduced consumption. Indeed in some cases (Such as improved central heating) consumption can actually increase <br>
<br>
For example I live in an Old house; it has solid walls, no insulation (Not really possible) and ill-fitting sash windows (I cant put modern windows in a 18th century building, They would look Horrible!) Last year I installed Gas central heating; previously I didn’t have any heating apart from <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>*a*</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> open fire. It was bloody cold!! But I lived with it by wearing extra clothing and even a woolly hat. <br>
<br>
With my new central heating I now live in a much warmer house. As a consequence I probably use at least the same amount of energy as I did before and probably rather more since now I heat the whole house rather than just the living room!<br>
<br>
I am not willing to remain as cold as I was before and translate my improved heating efficiency into reduced consumption! <br>
<br>
20 years ago my parents had cavity wall insulation installed, their result was much the same. No reduction in fuel consumption, but a somewhat warmer house.<br>
<br>
Also IIRC most electricity is currently used to power induction motors rather than lighting (I think lighting accounts for about 10% of overall consumption) there is little efficiency improvement possible on Induction motors, they are already about as good as they can get. (Though admittedly, the equipment the motors are driving may have room for improvement)<br>
<br>
Also power consumption profiles are likely to change in the future. <br>
<br>
My home is difficult to heat, so I use gas since it is relatively inexpensive. If I was to build a new house to the standards that I would like then I may well chose electric heating owing to simplicity, low maintenance and safety. IE more efficient buildings = increased electricity demand not decreased!<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Without massive life-saving transfusions of involuntary taxpayer cash it would not have teetered along as long as it has. Even with untold billions in support is in in freefall collapse in almost all countries.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Personally I regard Energy supply as a national security issue, like defence, and *far* too important to be left to the vagaries of market economics. If that means the government making long-term investment commitments (Subsidy if you like) then so be it! Gas Turbine power stations aren’t a better way of generating electricity; they are just a better way of making a fast buck. You are quite right that it is only in the more centralised economies where nuclear is making headways, it is only in this type of economy where the 20-30+ year view can be taken. The fact that they *are* taking this view and enthusiastically going Nuclear should be ringing warning bells all over the western world where private companies profit is considered more important than security of supply! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :purpleunhappy --><img src=http://www.smilies-world.de/Smilies/Smilies_klein_1/Smilies_klein_1_1/shakemitkopf.gif ALT=":purpleunhappy"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
In the UK, The (Nationalised) CEGB was content to have its Nuclear power stations merely cover their costs over their lifetime! Making large profits for shareholders over a short period was not a concern, ensuring long term security of supply was!  The only reason why BE is in trouble now is because there is no money in base load (and there never has been) and (Current) Nuclear stations cant really produce anything *but* base load. This didn’t matter for CEGB since they were looking at maintaining a complete integrated system using a mix of base load, day load and peak lopping systems (Such as pumped storage and gas turbines) With our current broken up industry, maintaining this mix is difficult if not impossible. The coal industry has collapsed, old nuclear stations are not planned to be replaced! Any new stations are likely to be Gas Turbine. If we use gas at this rate it will be all gone in 30 years. And then what? With the best will in the world, windmills and solar panels are not going to replace this amount of energy<br>
<br>
What is more we do not just have to consider merely supplying current electricity requirements. We have to consider that in 50-60 years time we will be having (somehow) to use non-fossil energy to make up for replacing <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>*all*</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> the energy currently supplied by fossil fuels, over 90% of our current requirements! <br>
<br>
Nuclear is not a particularly cheap way of making energy (Whether as electricity or as a thermal Hydrogen process). There is a lot of complex and demanding engineering involved and the entire fuel cycle has to be accounted for (Fossil plants only deal with the fuel cycle up to the point where the smoke goes up the chimney! Smoke, which includes very large quantities of radioactives and other noxious chemicals for that matter!) <br>
<br>
It is however one that we *Know* works and we *Know* has the capability to deliver the goods in the long term. This is most certainly *not* something we can reliably say for any of the alternatives!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
